---
name: workflow-tcr
description: "TCR (test && commit || revert) loop on a dedicated branch."
---

Run a TCR (test-commit-revert) loop on the current change. On every invocation:
run the test suite — if green, commit; if red, hard-revert all uncommitted changes.

> **TCR semantics**: test && commit || revert (Thoughtworks Radar Vol 33 — Trial).

## Pre-flight safety checks

**STOP immediately if any of the following is true:**

1. The current branch is `<%= mainBranch %>` (or any integration branch). TCR must only run
   on a dedicated TCR branch. Never run TCR on `<%= mainBranch %>`.

   ```bash
   git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD
   ```

2. There are no staged or unstaged changes. TCR has nothing to operate on.

3. The working tree has untracked files that are not covered by `.gitignore` and
   should not be auto-committed. Review `.gitignore` first.

   > **Note on untracked files**: `git add -u` (used below) only stages modifications
   > and deletions of already-tracked files — it will NOT stage new untracked files.
   > `git reset --hard` (used below) resets the index and working tree to `HEAD` for
   > tracked files but does NOT delete untracked files. If you must discard untracked
   > files too, inspect `.gitignore` first and then run `git clean -fd` manually —
   > TCR itself will not do that for you.

If all checks pass, proceed below.

## Instructions

### Step 1 — Run the test suite

```bash
<%= commands.test %>
```

### Step 2 — Branch on outcome

**If the test suite passes (exit code 0):**

Commit all current changes with a conventional commit message:

```bash
git add -u && git commit -m "tcr: <brief description of change>"
```

> This is the **user-invoked opt-in** to committing. Invoking this slash command
> constitutes explicit user consent per the project's "NEVER commit unless
> user-invoked" policy.

**If the test suite fails (exit code non-0):**

Hard-revert all uncommitted changes:

```bash
git reset --hard HEAD
```

> **WARNING — destructive operation**: `git reset --hard` permanently discards all
> uncommitted changes (staged and unstaged). This is intentional TCR behaviour —
> red tests mean the change is reverted so you start from a clean baseline.

### Step 3 — Report outcome

Print a one-line summary:

- On commit: `TCR: COMMITTED — <commit sha> — tests passed`
- On revert: `TCR: REVERTED — tests failed — working tree restored to HEAD`

## Verification rules

- **NEVER run TCR on `<%= mainBranch %>`** or any other protected / integration branch.
  Create a dedicated branch first:

  ```bash
  git checkout -b tcr/<short-kebab-description>
  ```

- **NEVER skip the pre-flight checks.** Skipping them risks committing broken code
  or reverting work on the wrong branch.
- Only tracked files modified in the current working tree are staged and committed
  (`git add -u` never touches untracked files, and `git reset --hard` does not remove
  them either). Do not manually stage unrelated files before invoking this command;
  if untracked files must be discarded, run `git clean -fd` explicitly.
- Do not suppress or ignore test failures to avoid a revert. The revert IS the
  workflow — it forces a clean state so the next attempt can succeed.

## `git reset --hard` and the deny list

The repository's `.claude/settings.local.json` (or equivalent) may include
`git reset --hard` in the tool deny list (project baseline deny list). If so, Claude Code
will block the revert step and ask for approval.

**When the deny list blocks the revert:**

1. Claude Code surfaces a permission prompt.
2. The user must grant per-invocation approval for `git reset --hard` to proceed.
3. Do NOT work around this by using `git checkout -- .` or `git restore .` as a
   substitute — they do not reset the index, which breaks TCR semantics.
4. If approval is not granted, abort the TCR loop and report:
   `TCR: ABORTED — git reset --hard blocked by deny list`

To run TCR without per-invocation prompts, the user must explicitly add
`git reset --hard` to the allow list in `.claude/settings.local.json` for this
project. This is an intentional friction point — TCR's hard-revert is destructive
and should require conscious user opt-in at the tool level.

## Git rules

- **NEVER commit or push without explicit user invocation** — invoking this
  slash command IS the user's explicit invocation for the commit step.
- **NEVER run on `<%= mainBranch %>`.** All TCR work stays on a dedicated branch.
- Only exception for additional git operations: merging `<%= mainBranch %>` to resolve
  conflicts before starting a TCR session.
